Now for the fun part...
 let's move over to the budget next.

<<Budget>>

Let's tour your budget screen... Here you can see the current month as well as previous and future months.

<<Budget>>

Let's say you want to compare several months at once. You can click on the calendars to view one, two, or more months at a time. Please click the third calendar icon.

<<Budget>>

Now you can view 3 months. Let's change the view so you can see a different set of 3 months using the purple selection.
System moves avatar to purple months selected

<<Budget>>

Below the current month, there are several pieces of information and an amount labeled "To Assign".

<<Budget>>

While you're getting used to coaching on this platform, just focus on the amount to assign for now.

<<Budget>>

Click on the purple number to see some options for this amount. There are multiple ways to move money around your budget. After all, it's meant to be flexible!

<<Budget>>

You can click anywhere outside of this box to close it. We'll move onto an overview of the budget table!

<<Accounts>>

You can update the name of your budget up here.

<<Accounts>>

Great! Next up, let's practice adding a transaction on your checking account. Please click on your checking account to get started!

<<Accounts>>

For checking account transactions, payments DECREASE the balance and deposits INCREASE the balance.

<<Accounts>>

Click "+ Add New" and type "Kroger" as your Payee.

<<Accounts>>

For the category, select "Groceries". Now, enter $120 in the Payment box.

<<Accounts>>

Finish this transaction by hitting the check mark to turn it green. Then, click "Add". You can hit "Cancel" to get out of adding transactions.

<<Accounts>>

Let's delete this pretend transaction. Go ahead and select the checkbox next to this payment and click "Delete".

<<Budget>>

The Category column houses the names of each category. We'll get customizing these in a bit.

<<Budget>>

The Budgeted column is where you'll be budgeting your dollars. This shows you what you have allocated each month for the categories.

<<Budget>>

Next up is the Spent column. This shows you what you've actually spent out of the budgeted dollars.

<<Budget>>

The last column is Balance.This shows you what you have available to spend. If it's negative and red, you've overspent in this category. If the amount is black, that's what you have available.

<<Budget>>

No red allowed! If you don't cover this overspending, you risk over-drafting your checking account and that's a no-no around here.

<<Budget>>

Take a look at the three dots. This gives you visual options. You can collapse and expand category groups. You can also show and hide Hidden categories.

<<Budget>>

Alright, now add a category to this group, if needed. Click that arrow again, and add a category that you may need but is not listed.

<<Budget>>

Ok, I'll leave you alone for a while but keep up the good work... and don't forget to give a job to every dollar.

<<Budget>>

This is the budget table, basically a digital cash envelope system! You create categories relevant to your life and assign dollars accordingly. Let's do a quick tutorial.
